'''Erik Krag''' (1902 &ndash; 1987) was a Norwegian literary historian, translator, novelist and playwright. He was born in [[Copenhagen]], a son of novelist [[Thomas Krag]] and poet Iben Nielsen. Krag is known as the founder of [[Slavic language|Slavic]] literary history as academic discipline in Norway. He was a professor at the [[University of Oslo]] from 1946 to 1969. His monography  ''Dostojevskij'' from 1962 was translated into [[English language|English]] in 1976, and he has also published works on [[Leo Tolstoi]] and on Russian theatre.<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Erik Krag |encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo |url=http://www.snl.no/Erik_Krag |language=Norwegian | accessdate=24 July 2011 }}</ref><ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Erik Krag |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Geir |last=Kjetsaa |authorlink=Geir Kjetsaa |editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo |url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Erik_Krag/utdypning|language=Norwegian |accessdate=24 July 2011}}</ref>

